WEBVTT

00:04.756 --> 00:32.866
[SPEAKER_01]: Hello and welcome to Veterans of the Valley.

00:32.886 --> 00:33.987
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm Tom Turveyville.

00:34.844 --> 00:38.729
[SPEAKER_01]: Look up Marine in the dictionary and you might just see a picture of Jim West.

00:38.749 --> 00:39.590
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, you certainly should.

00:40.131 --> 00:44.837
[SPEAKER_01]: This former Madisonville police chief spent nearly three years as a ground fighter in Vietnam.

00:44.857 --> 00:47.680
[SPEAKER_01]: Didn't come home until he'd been wounded three times.

00:47.700 --> 00:50.744
[SPEAKER_01]: Jim West was not a spit and polish kind of Marine at all.

00:50.764 --> 00:55.310
[SPEAKER_00]: He was a fighter who didn't mind bending a rule or two if it meant protecting his fellow Marine.

00:56.051 --> 01:00.837
[SPEAKER_00]: You would go to war anytime with this Brazos Valley veteran, and you're about to find out why.

01:00.857 --> 01:01.898
[SPEAKER_00]: Welcome, Jim West.

01:02.114 --> 01:03.395
[SPEAKER_00]: to veterans of the valley.

01:03.475 --> 01:06.037
[SPEAKER_01]: It is indeed an honor to have you and to know you.

01:06.078 --> 01:07.959
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's talk about your early years.

01:07.979 --> 01:16.307
[SPEAKER_01]: You were born and raised near Muskogee, Oklahoma, and when you were just barely out of high school, you decided to join up in 1959, join the Marines.

01:16.727 --> 01:19.710
[SPEAKER_00]: Talk a little bit about that decision, why you decided to join up.

01:19.730 --> 01:31.480
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, I got tired of milking cows from the folks on the dairy farm, and I went out and ventured out into the steel to work in the machine shop or whatever.

01:31.882 --> 01:57.990
[SPEAKER_01]: learn a trade and they had the steel strike in 59 so two or three of my buddies said Wes let's just go into service well my two heroes my two cousins they had fought in Korea one came out of the Chosen Reservoir with the 1st Marine Division and one fought with the 1st Cav in the Battle of the Yellow River and he was captured and I studied these

01:58.493 --> 02:05.341
[SPEAKER_01]: men through my aunts and uncles, and it gave me the Spree de Corps.

02:06.523 --> 02:07.264
[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed.

02:07.284 --> 02:09.146
[SPEAKER_01]: I joined the Marine Corps in 1959.

02:09.927 --> 02:14.653
[SPEAKER_01]: You told me your dad was a World War II vet, your uncles were veterans, your family worked for Douglas Aircraft.

02:15.133 --> 02:16.094
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

02:16.595 --> 02:28.129
[SPEAKER_01]: All the men was fighting in the war, and the grandparents took care of us on the farm, and the women, they worked at Douglas Aircraft Company, driving rivets and welding and helped the war effort.

02:29.054 --> 02:36.809
[SPEAKER_01]: And sometimes they brought some German prisoners out to work on the farms to help while the men were fighting.

02:36.829 --> 02:41.558
[SPEAKER_01]: And that gave me an understanding of what my country is all about.

02:41.779 --> 02:43.041
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

02:43.061 --> 02:48.532
[SPEAKER_01]: You said your dad sent you a toy B-17 bomber and you got to play with that and that sort of gave you the itch also, right?

02:48.572 --> 02:48.832
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

02:48.852 --> 02:50.235
[SPEAKER_01]: He sent that back from England.

02:51.245 --> 03:03.717
[SPEAKER_01]: First duty station was in Hawaii, and this was 1959, really, before a lot of people had heard of what was going on in Southeast Asia or Vietnam or Laos or any of those countries, at least people in the United States.

03:03.737 --> 03:06.700
[SPEAKER_01]: So when you first started out, you were over in the Pacific area.

03:06.720 --> 03:09.503
[SPEAKER_01]: I know you spent some time in Okinawa and Borneo.

03:09.563 --> 03:12.245
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about sort of the days before Vietnam.

03:12.265 --> 03:20.273
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, I got an assignment to Hawaii for three years, and everybody in my

03:20.675 --> 03:27.181
[SPEAKER_01]: Graduating Mattoon got a little upset because everybody says, well, that's one of the greatest places to have a good time.

03:27.281 --> 03:40.333
[SPEAKER_01]: And then all at once, we got a, I guess you'd call scuttlebutt that there was something happening over in Southeast Asia, especially Laos, Cambodia, and Vietnam.

03:41.014 --> 03:46.879
[SPEAKER_01]: But we was not told that we had advisors already in Vietnam.

03:46.899 --> 03:48.741
[SPEAKER_01]: So they changed my orders to Okinawa.

03:49.463 --> 04:02.822
[SPEAKER_01]: I went into anti-tank weapons section, and from there we made landings in the Philippines, went to North Barneo where they had an insurrection of Indonesian rebels.

04:02.882 --> 04:16.261
[SPEAKER_01]: We're kind of messing with the Dutch colony, so they sent us there with the Australian and British Royal Marines, and we scared them back up in the mountains and stayed there for about almost a month and a month and a half.

04:17.523 --> 04:19.285
[SPEAKER_01]: And that was called the Osito Pack.

04:19.568 --> 04:19.868
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

04:20.810 --> 04:23.514
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's kind of like the NATO PAC, but it's called CETO PAC.

04:23.774 --> 04:32.046
[SPEAKER_01]: We had certain Oriental nations there that was combined in our effort to keep communism kind of at bay.

04:33.649 --> 04:39.457
[SPEAKER_01]: And then we slowly got scuttlebutt that the Vietnam was starting to turn into a crisis.

04:39.477 --> 04:39.597
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

04:39.617 --> 04:46.808
[SPEAKER_01]: Due to we had Marine and Army and Special Forces in there as advisors and

04:47.193 --> 04:50.557
[SPEAKER_01]: I felt the feeling that we was going to have trouble.

04:50.577 --> 04:52.459
[SPEAKER_01]: And the Marines are always first to fight.

04:52.639 --> 04:54.762
[SPEAKER_01]: We're the presidents on.

04:54.782 --> 04:59.567
[SPEAKER_01]: Some people call us the presidents Doberman Pinchers, and he's success on them.

04:59.587 --> 05:11.161
[SPEAKER_01]: When anything in America has trouble with our freedom, our own lives, whatever, to help other people that want to be free.

05:12.322 --> 05:16.727
[SPEAKER_01]: And then the Chinese started shelling the island of Kamui, which is Taiwan.

05:17.416 --> 05:39.498
[SPEAKER_01]: long-range artillery so we had a FMF pack fleet marine force we went up there and cruised around a little bit to let China know that if they tried to invade we would protect the island of Formosa which everybody calls Taiwan because we had interest in that as a kind of a territorial.

05:39.618 --> 05:46.765
[SPEAKER_01]: After the Korean War that's the people who enjoyed the American way of life moved to Taiwan and

05:47.183 --> 05:49.065
[SPEAKER_01]: Communists took over the main island.

05:49.586 --> 05:57.735
[SPEAKER_00]: I want to get you to Vietnam in a little bit, but before Vietnam, I guess in 1962 or so, there was a Cuban crisis.

05:57.755 --> 05:57.975
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, sir.

05:57.995 --> 06:01.699
[SPEAKER_00]: And I know that you were involved in the state of Florida in that.

06:01.719 --> 06:03.501
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk a little bit about that.

06:03.521 --> 06:11.950
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, I had my 15-month tour in the Orient, and all at once I got orders to report down in Florida.

06:13.211 --> 06:16.515
[SPEAKER_01]: And it was a base that required a...

06:16.765 --> 06:17.867
[SPEAKER_01]: top secret clearance.

06:19.048 --> 06:32.768
[SPEAKER_01]: So the unbecoming of me being a combat man, and I love my grunt attitude, or what are you going to call it, Marine Corps, I went down there and received a top secret clearance.

06:32.888 --> 06:39.718
[SPEAKER_01]: And my mother wrote me a letter and said, son, how come the Navy intelligence people has come to my house, our house,

06:40.610 --> 06:46.098
[SPEAKER_01]: and wanted to know if you had any records of school records, report cards.

06:46.118 --> 06:49.383
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, my blessed mother kept them in an old cedar chest.

06:50.645 --> 06:57.235
[SPEAKER_01]: So she let them have them and they went and talked to some of my school teachers and everything before I knew it, I had a top secret clearance.

06:58.210 --> 07:02.920
[SPEAKER_01]: And then we had the nuclear weapon in the film being taken at Cuba, flying in.

07:03.000 --> 07:13.080
[SPEAKER_01]: We protected that and took care of that in the security part, which was not really being able to explain some of that stuff.

07:13.381 --> 07:21.936
[SPEAKER_01]: 1963 or thereabouts, you'd been in for four years, and you had a decision to make, whether you were going to go back to Oklahoma and get a job, or whether you were going to stay in the Marines.

07:22.297 --> 07:22.477
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, sir.

07:22.497 --> 07:23.960
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about that decision to stay.

07:23.980 --> 07:34.698
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, my four years was up, and I was extended a year by President Kennedy for the Cuban crisis, and that's coming up 15 days prior to getting out on five years.

07:36.101 --> 07:37.363
[SPEAKER_01]: I was going to be a...

07:37.782 --> 07:43.028
[SPEAKER_01]: Get in school of the Highway Patrol, Oklahoma Highway Patrol, because they were kind of a breed of their own.

07:43.048 --> 07:46.712
[SPEAKER_01]: A lot of former Marines and Special Forces.

07:47.493 --> 07:55.902
[SPEAKER_01]: And I enjoyed them because I had a young man that was a good friend of mine that played baseball, football with me, that became a Highway Patrolman.

07:55.922 --> 07:57.964
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'd see him when I came home on leave.

07:59.206 --> 08:00.507
[SPEAKER_01]: And I used to ride with him.

08:00.527 --> 08:07.435
[SPEAKER_01]: And my sheriff, Dave Faulkner, would debutize me and take me sometimes with him.

08:08.005 --> 08:10.410
[SPEAKER_01]: when I was on home and on leave.

08:11.492 --> 08:23.718
[SPEAKER_01]: So law enforcement started kind of coming through my mind and my feelings about that's my job, to protect and serve, even in the Marine Corps or back in the States.

08:23.738 --> 08:27.887
[SPEAKER_01]: But my major and my sergeant major, who I played tennis with my major,

08:28.846 --> 08:38.635
[SPEAKER_01]: in Pensacola, Florida and other places when we had a chance and they took me out and we got a little social inebriated at a golf course and I shipped over for six years.

08:39.336 --> 08:56.271
[SPEAKER_01]: So I become a Marine and full hearted and I felt why should I give up five years of my life when I knew the job and I enjoyed it and it made me feel good to be kind of doing a job for my country and our way of life.

08:56.960 --> 08:58.982
[SPEAKER_01]: They sent me to drill instructor school.

08:59.503 --> 09:08.933
[SPEAKER_01]: But my shipping over, I wanted to go to guerrilla warfare school because I knew something was going to happen in the back of my mind in Southeast Asia.

09:09.374 --> 09:11.015
[SPEAKER_01]: I felt it come over me.

09:11.035 --> 09:17.362
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know if it was just something that I read about or whatever.

09:18.704 --> 09:24.250
[SPEAKER_01]: And I remember friends of mine I was serving with who was in Cuba when Castro took over in 59.

09:25.242 --> 09:32.430
[SPEAKER_01]: when the Marines were down there and they were told not to go on liberty because Castro took over and Batista flew out to Spain.

09:34.092 --> 09:36.814
[SPEAKER_01]: And then I was assigned to the drilling truck to school.

09:37.315 --> 09:38.717
[SPEAKER_01]: I was there, went through the school.

09:39.738 --> 09:43.942
[SPEAKER_01]: But yet my feelings was I didn't want to instruct Marines.

09:44.042 --> 09:44.843
[SPEAKER_01]: I wanted to fight.

09:45.784 --> 09:50.369
[SPEAKER_01]: I wanted to be in the front lines as most Marines, you know, you're first to fight.

09:51.691 --> 09:53.072
[SPEAKER_01]: So they sent me to Europe.

09:53.761 --> 09:58.127
[SPEAKER_01]: And I went over there with the Fleet and Marine Force.

09:58.147 --> 10:03.315
[SPEAKER_01]: And we landed in Palma, Spain, Madrid, Spain, Genoa, Italy, Toulon, France.

10:04.096 --> 10:13.390
[SPEAKER_01]: I was on a flagship with a Commodore and his Fleet Admiral on the USS Sanctuary.

10:13.657 --> 10:16.161
[SPEAKER_01]: Felt like then I wasn't a seagulling Marine.

10:16.781 --> 10:21.248
[SPEAKER_01]: They call us Leathernecks because we wore the old leather back in the 1700s.

10:21.788 --> 10:26.856
[SPEAKER_01]: But I was more of a hard-nosed Marine.

10:27.637 --> 10:29.159
[SPEAKER_01]: I felt it inside of me.

10:29.179 --> 10:37.691
[SPEAKER_01]: So they sent me to the Drill Warfare School, come back, and I went through Fort Sherman, Panama Canal, Green Berets, where I had instructors.

10:38.692 --> 10:40.395
[SPEAKER_01]: And from there, I went to Vietnam.

10:41.616 --> 10:42.718
[SPEAKER_01]: But I had this talent.

10:42.968 --> 10:50.382
[SPEAKER_01]: that I knew what enemy we was going to fight because our country never really understood guerrilla warfare, I don't believe.

10:51.504 --> 11:01.782
[SPEAKER_01]: But the Marines fought in the Banana Wars in Cuba way back in the 1920s or 30s or whatever.

11:01.802 --> 11:05.449
[SPEAKER_01]: So I could read that history, also going through the training.

11:06.205 --> 11:12.051
[SPEAKER_00]: You spent some two and a half years in Vietnam, and as we said from the outset, you were seriously wounded three times.

11:12.071 --> 11:13.993
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, sir.

11:14.434 --> 11:15.835
[SPEAKER_01]: You earned three Purple Hearts.

11:15.855 --> 11:17.276
[SPEAKER_01]: You took two of them, I believe.

11:17.537 --> 11:18.017
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

11:18.037 --> 11:20.220
[SPEAKER_01]: I did not want my mother to suffer.

11:21.781 --> 11:23.002
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about that if you can again.

11:23.022 --> 11:24.484
[SPEAKER_01]: You talked about that the other day.

11:25.165 --> 11:35.115
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, I had a corpsman I was hit with shrapnel in the arms, and I said, Doc, don't you ever give me another Purple Heart unless I'm in a body bag because my mother,

11:35.365 --> 11:38.628
[SPEAKER_01]: I felt more about her than I did myself.

11:40.490 --> 11:41.791
[SPEAKER_01]: So he agreed with me.

11:42.172 --> 11:44.934
[SPEAKER_01]: He looked at me one time and that's all he needed to say.

11:45.035 --> 11:48.298
[SPEAKER_01]: You didn't want that car to pull up in front of your mama's house again.

11:48.578 --> 11:49.759
[SPEAKER_01]: No, I can understand that.

11:50.160 --> 11:54.484
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about when you were wounded, the first time that you were wounded.

11:54.504 --> 12:00.590
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, the first time I was wounded, we had Viet Cong hitting convoys.

12:01.190 --> 12:03.853
[SPEAKER_01]: I was at High Van Pass, just about

12:04.525 --> 12:08.511
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, 60 miles from Da Nang on Route 1 going to Way City.

12:09.171 --> 12:18.564
[SPEAKER_01]: And a lot of the convoys was coming through there was Arvin and the local VC was hitting them pretty bad, ambushing them.

12:18.585 --> 12:26.696
[SPEAKER_01]: A friend of mine, Sergeant Kent, was down at the Esso plant where Brown and Root opened it back up after the French shut it down.

12:26.716 --> 12:27.597
[SPEAKER_01]: And he had a

12:28.538 --> 12:36.487
[SPEAKER_01]: PF, we call PFs, Preventional Forces, who were brought into the South Vietnamese Army as security in villages.

12:37.148 --> 12:40.672
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, he had that attachment with four Marines.

12:40.692 --> 12:42.154
[SPEAKER_01]: He was killed that night.

12:42.214 --> 12:50.083
[SPEAKER_01]: They ambushed him, and he was talking to me on the radio, and I was farther up up the hill, but I could not go to help him.

12:50.103 --> 12:55.069
[SPEAKER_01]: And he was shot twice in the back, and while he was still talking to me on the radio.

12:55.876 --> 13:00.281
[SPEAKER_01]: So I knew then something was going to happen up in our area.

13:00.301 --> 13:07.869
[SPEAKER_01]: And one day I come back and we had a kind of a chow hall there with Hawk missile sites just above us and we had their protection.

13:08.570 --> 13:13.296
[SPEAKER_01]: And we also had the guard dogs running through the fence at nighttime helping us.

13:14.957 --> 13:19.943
[SPEAKER_01]: And the Viet Cong come out on the road and knocked out three

13:20.581 --> 13:24.745
[SPEAKER_01]: South Vietnamese trucks with RPG rounds and machine guns.

13:24.765 --> 13:29.310
[SPEAKER_01]: And I had a 50 up there on the hill, so I cut down on the 50 on them.

13:29.330 --> 13:33.374
[SPEAKER_01]: And the Arvin lieutenant and warrant officer was hollering at me.

13:33.575 --> 13:36.758
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, I couldn't hear them hollering, but they was waving their hand to help them.

13:36.778 --> 13:39.501
[SPEAKER_01]: So I just turned the 50 on them, the enemy.

13:40.021 --> 13:45.407
[SPEAKER_01]: And they presented me with the Vietnamese cross of Gallandry with POM.

13:46.298 --> 13:51.424
[SPEAKER_01]: And then when we went down there to check them, we found eight Arvinds dead and three wounded.

13:53.066 --> 13:54.328
[SPEAKER_01]: And we got them medevaced.

13:54.949 --> 13:59.414
[SPEAKER_01]: So they gave me an honor over it, which to me, I was just doing my job.

13:59.654 --> 14:01.136
[SPEAKER_00]: You weren't fighting for medals?

14:01.156 --> 14:01.677
[SPEAKER_01]: No, sir.

14:01.697 --> 14:05.361
[SPEAKER_01]: I was fighting for their way of life and ours to be free.

14:05.381 --> 14:06.142
[SPEAKER_01]: Exactly.

14:06.162 --> 14:07.063
[SPEAKER_01]: Exactly.

14:07.083 --> 14:11.749
[SPEAKER_00]: We're going to take a pause here and take a look at some pictures that you gave us.

14:12.151 --> 14:15.516
[SPEAKER_00]: from your time in Vietnam and even afterwards.

