[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

18:01.293 --> 18:09.201
[SPEAKER_01]: And there, when I was working at Marine Liaison, the commanding commandant of the Marine Corps, he came in to visit us.

18:09.221 --> 18:10.622
[SPEAKER_01]: And he had a little talk with us.

18:10.682 --> 18:19.390
[SPEAKER_01]: And there's some of the officers he's checking there that flew the F-4 Phantoms that were hit and wounded in the arms and legs from shrapnel artillery.

18:20.045 --> 18:27.775
[SPEAKER_01]: or anti-tank guns or whatever they used to knock them down.

18:27.795 --> 18:36.505
[SPEAKER_01]: And the officers had the quarters up at the sixth floor and we took care of them, made sure they got their pay and whatever till they recovered.

18:36.525 --> 18:40.530
[SPEAKER_01]: And most of the officers wanted to run around with us grunts and drank with us.

18:40.550 --> 18:48.280
[SPEAKER_01]: And they'd like to go down to staff club and have a hoorah with us because they knew that the grunts were down there really fighting.

18:48.833 --> 18:50.596
[SPEAKER_01]: You can see your left hand there, this bandage.

18:50.616 --> 18:51.137
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

18:51.277 --> 18:52.319
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm still working on it.

18:52.379 --> 18:53.781
[SPEAKER_01]: Including this picture.

18:53.801 --> 18:54.923
[SPEAKER_01]: That's President Kennedy.

18:55.704 --> 19:02.536
[SPEAKER_01]: I was an MP at the time, and I got the chance to kind of guard the crowd while he made his tour through.

19:03.537 --> 19:07.864
[SPEAKER_01]: And that was the last time he was able to walk the grounds.

19:10.990 --> 19:11.871
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, let's move on.

19:13.538 --> 19:19.007
[SPEAKER_00]: There's a very familiar figure on the left side of that photo, and you're in the middle talking about San Diego, right?

19:19.027 --> 19:19.187
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

19:19.207 --> 19:24.856
[SPEAKER_01]: I had the Naval Hospital, the Admiral, wanted me to present the GI Joe Award to Bob Hope.

19:24.876 --> 19:31.646
[SPEAKER_01]: But due to my wounds there, I could not handle, at the time, my left hand.

19:32.588 --> 19:35.412
[SPEAKER_01]: So we talked to Sergeant Franson.

19:35.847 --> 20:05.466
[SPEAKER_01]: that he'd do it and uh there was let's see i think four of us there that some of them were just the survivors out of the whole platoon the whole platoon was wiped out but the dock there and a corpsman and a few other ones right so they was given that at padre island in san diego and the owner of padre ball team walked up and gave me 700 free tickets for all the wounded marines to go to the ball

20:06.172 --> 20:10.217
[SPEAKER_01]: He gave me a press tag where I could set up with the press and all that.

20:11.378 --> 20:13.100
[SPEAKER_01]: But I was in a lot of pain then.

20:13.161 --> 20:16.184
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't participate in a lot of that stuff.

20:16.685 --> 20:17.466
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a great picture.

20:17.726 --> 20:20.289
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, I think we've got, there's the wrestling.

20:20.309 --> 20:31.082
[SPEAKER_01]: There's when I, A&M coach there, went to A&M, and he was a captain in the Marines, and he was a coach, and that's my lieutenant I'm getting ready to slam on the mat.

20:32.164 --> 20:34.947
[SPEAKER_01]: And I had a pretty good time of keeping a,

20:35.281 --> 20:40.466
[SPEAKER_01]: heavyweight championship going for a while there until I said that was enough.

20:41.987 --> 20:44.089
[SPEAKER_01]: My first sergeant didn't like jockstrapers.

20:44.109 --> 20:51.195
[SPEAKER_01]: He wanted us out in the field training all the time instead of playing what you call the high school games or the kind of stuff.

20:51.916 --> 20:54.758
[SPEAKER_01]: He was known in World War II and Korean vet.

20:54.778 --> 20:57.681
[SPEAKER_00]: This is later on when you were at Madisonville?

20:57.701 --> 20:57.961
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

20:57.981 --> 21:04.967
[SPEAKER_01]: There's my good buddy there next to President Bush who was running for governor the second time.

21:05.386 --> 21:22.389
[SPEAKER_01]: He was a county judge down in Beeville, and he was my youngest Marine in my battalion in Vietnam, and he was wounded, shot through both hips and lost six foot of his intestines, and they built him hips back up, and they can do miracles nowadays.

21:22.409 --> 21:26.114
[SPEAKER_01]: And we was together in a hospital down in Corpus Christi Naval Hospital.

21:26.775 --> 21:33.925
[SPEAKER_01]: So he got up on his feet, made county judge, and George W. Bush come down there to the Big Kings Ranch,

21:34.765 --> 21:37.950
[SPEAKER_01]: And Beeville and all them people, we had 3,000 people there.

21:38.230 --> 21:39.151
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

21:39.171 --> 21:45.220
[SPEAKER_01]: And we had the big Texas barbecue, my first introduction to a Texas barbecue.

21:45.240 --> 21:49.546
[SPEAKER_01]: And George W. wanted to shake hands with me and talk to me a little bit.

21:50.647 --> 21:54.533
[SPEAKER_01]: He asked me what he should do to win the governorship.

21:54.613 --> 21:58.058
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, sir, there's an old saying about the Marine Corps.

21:59.059 --> 22:03.085
[SPEAKER_01]: You promise three things and do them, you'll survive.

22:03.554 --> 22:08.527
[SPEAKER_01]: But if you promise 15 or 20 and can't accomplish them, you're lost.

22:08.547 --> 22:10.973
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's a word I had to say to him.

22:10.993 --> 22:12.658
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a good advice.

22:12.678 --> 22:13.159
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

22:14.945 --> 22:17.307
[SPEAKER_01]: And there's all the badges I wore.

22:17.327 --> 22:19.669
[SPEAKER_01]: There's one badge I don't have there.

22:20.030 --> 22:25.895
[SPEAKER_01]: That's assistant chief badge because I never got it back from the city.

22:26.135 --> 22:36.124
[SPEAKER_01]: But there's a patrolman, sergeant, chief, deputy, and chief constable, chief deputy constable.

22:36.144 --> 22:42.069
[SPEAKER_00]: And this was your law enforcement in Madison County was really your career up until just a few months ago.

22:42.089 --> 22:43.531
[SPEAKER_01]: 23 and a half years.

22:43.691 --> 22:44.051
[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed.

22:44.452 --> 22:44.952
[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed.

22:44.932 --> 22:47.995
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's go back to Vietnam, if we can.

22:48.015 --> 22:53.219
[SPEAKER_01]: I want to talk after your first injury, when you were first wounded.

22:53.239 --> 22:59.725
[SPEAKER_01]: You got the word that your unit was moving out and wanted to know whether you were going to stay in the hospital or whether you were going to go.

23:00.565 --> 23:03.888
[SPEAKER_01]: And contrary to the doctor's orders, you went.

23:03.908 --> 23:04.388
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

23:04.408 --> 23:05.990
[SPEAKER_01]: I was in the Charlie Med.

23:06.851 --> 23:10.133
[SPEAKER_01]: We call it just B Med or Battalion Med.

23:10.714 --> 23:14.517
[SPEAKER_01]: But we call it Charlie Med just for Marine Corps jargon.

23:14.918 --> 23:18.764
[SPEAKER_01]: And the doctor told me, he says, you now, you're going to stay in your bed.

23:19.025 --> 23:21.068
[SPEAKER_01]: You've got a drain in your leg from the wound.

23:21.929 --> 23:28.901
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll give you a chit for two beers at the little old club that the Vietnamese, we gave them see ration to make us.

23:28.921 --> 23:32.947
[SPEAKER_01]: So I had my two beers and the old sergeant was running it.

23:32.967 --> 23:36.172
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, no, two beers for a platoon sergeant ain't enough.

23:36.192 --> 23:36.974
[SPEAKER_01]: I need at least four.

23:38.656 --> 23:39.638
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'd have four beers.

23:40.780 --> 23:41.601
[SPEAKER_01]: So...

23:42.205 --> 23:43.006
[SPEAKER_01]: I got on the horn.

23:43.447 --> 23:52.498
[SPEAKER_01]: I got the word that my unit was moving up to Kason, and I didn't want to be left behind because I'd be transferred over to another unit.

23:53.579 --> 23:57.885
[SPEAKER_01]: So I got on the Lima Lima line, cranked it, and got to my what we call a lamb line.

23:59.166 --> 24:06.255
[SPEAKER_01]: Got a hold of my first sergeant and my skipper, captain, said, send your jeep and come get me.

24:07.957 --> 24:11.962
[SPEAKER_01]: And the Jeep showed up about an hour, 30 minutes, 40 minutes, or whatever.

24:12.222 --> 24:13.443
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't keep time on that.

24:13.463 --> 24:20.291
[SPEAKER_01]: And he showed up, and I just got in the Jeep, and my doctor, Lieutenant Commander, hollered, I'll court-martial you, Marine.

24:20.992 --> 24:23.034
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not responsible if you lose that leg.

24:24.856 --> 24:29.242
[SPEAKER_01]: So I said, Lieutenant Commander, what are you going to do, shave my head and give me another tour of duty?

24:30.143 --> 24:32.445
[SPEAKER_01]: And I told the driver to take off.

24:32.465 --> 24:33.326
[SPEAKER_01]: And you saluted him?

24:33.667 --> 24:34.027
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, sir.

24:34.047 --> 24:36.630
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, all due respect to your title and your rank, sir.

24:37.505 --> 24:44.031
[SPEAKER_01]: And I had my corpsman pull out a little bit of the drain and cut it off so it healed from the inside out.

24:44.051 --> 24:52.218
[SPEAKER_01]: Believe it or not, we're starting to get low on time, but I want to talk about the last time that you were wounded, wounded in the shoulder, and that's wounds that you still deal with today.

24:52.298 --> 24:53.239
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about that.

24:53.299 --> 24:57.963
[SPEAKER_01]: We landed up at the Gill Inn and Conti Inn by the DMZ.

24:58.383 --> 25:04.509
[SPEAKER_01]: We call it the McNamara Line because we had a barbed wire all across it in towers.

25:05.490 --> 25:06.010
[SPEAKER_01]: Well,

25:06.226 --> 25:13.254
[SPEAKER_01]: North Vietnamese B-24th B Division moved in and they had overrun Bravo 1-9.

25:14.655 --> 25:17.418
[SPEAKER_01]: And if you ever heard of Bravo 1-9, you read it.

25:18.880 --> 25:22.684
[SPEAKER_01]: They call it the Death Battalion because they lost so many people.

25:24.026 --> 25:25.688
[SPEAKER_01]: But they killed Ho Chi Minh's son.

25:26.709 --> 25:35.018
[SPEAKER_01]: So the word came out to North Vietnamese to always find out where Bravo Company 1-9 was and try to annihilate them because of that

25:35.521 --> 25:37.263
[SPEAKER_01]: what they did and they killed O.C.

25:37.283 --> 25:37.864
[SPEAKER_01]: Bent's son.

25:38.985 --> 25:52.360
[SPEAKER_01]: Well we went up there to help them and the second platoon landed in Hilo area Sparrow and we come in Hilo area Canary and they had almost been overrun completely.

25:53.441 --> 26:01.410
[SPEAKER_01]: So they were wearing marine flight jackets and marine helmets to try to keep us from distinguishing them from our men.

26:02.285 --> 26:09.399
[SPEAKER_01]: And all at once, machine gun opened up, and they rushed us, and it was just slowly trying to take out as many as they could.

26:10.441 --> 26:18.657
[SPEAKER_01]: And I got my platoon down, and I got hit in the arm, three rounds in the pack, one through a canteen, one in a magazine pouch, and it exploded.

26:19.582 --> 26:23.428
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's like something picked me up and just shook me like firecrackers going off in me.

26:23.968 --> 26:29.296
[SPEAKER_01]: Jim, this has gone way too quickly, but I know that from there you had to leave Vietnam.

26:29.316 --> 26:30.238
[SPEAKER_01]: You went to San Diego.

26:30.278 --> 26:33.522
[SPEAKER_01]: We talked a little bit about how you were a liaison with other Marines.

26:33.602 --> 26:38.209
[SPEAKER_01]: Your career continued as you were even a contestant on the dating game.

26:38.229 --> 26:39.892
[SPEAKER_01]: And you met many a Hollywood star.

26:40.012 --> 26:49.065
[SPEAKER_01]: I met Jonathan Winters, Don DeFord, Charlton Heston, who was the president of the Theater Guild.

26:49.433 --> 26:50.995
[SPEAKER_01]: David Jensen.

26:51.015 --> 26:56.340
[SPEAKER_01]: Not only did you meet them, but the honor was for them to meet you.

26:56.440 --> 26:58.322
[SPEAKER_01]: It was motivation.

26:58.662 --> 26:59.783
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's our honor to meet you, too.

26:59.803 --> 27:01.204
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm sorry that we are out of time.

27:01.224 --> 27:02.766
[SPEAKER_01]: But thank you, Jim West, for your service.

27:02.786 --> 27:03.246
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, sir.

27:03.346 --> 27:04.087
[SPEAKER_01]: It's my pleasure.

27:04.127 --> 27:05.208
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

27:05.228 --> 27:06.369
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm young and strong.

27:06.489 --> 27:07.911
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll be 66 this year.

27:08.391 --> 27:15.458
[SPEAKER_01]: Jim West and his wife, Mary Beth, live in rural Madison County, where family pictures hang on the wall and memories of his service remain pretty clear.

27:15.927 --> 27:25.278
[SPEAKER_00]: If it weren't for those wounds he suffered 30 years ago, he says that even at the age of 66, he'd volunteer to fight in Iraq for his country and the freedoms we all enjoy.

27:25.298 --> 27:32.086
[SPEAKER_00]: We salute Jim West for his military service and his civil service, and we thank all veterans, and thanks to our underwriter, First National Bank.

27:32.467 --> 27:37.333
[SPEAKER_00]: You can read other stories of veterans in the Brazos Valley in Brazos Valley Heroes each Sunday in the Eagle.

27:37.793 --> 27:39.355
[SPEAKER_00]: For Jim West, I'm Tom Turbeville.

27:39.375 --> 27:41.698
[SPEAKER_00]: We'll see you next time on Veterans of the Valley.

27:56.562 --> 28:14.723
Amen.

